{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488725"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"518"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/518"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.47,0.2,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102709"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/518"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9042"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102709"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with intense pain in his right eye which has come on gradually over the previous 12 hours. He has no history of ocular issues and is otherwise well. He has no significant medical history, takes no regular medications and has no known drug allergies.,\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, vitals are within normal limits. The pupil responds to light. The visual acuity in the right eye is 6/12 and in the left eye is 6/6. Fluorescein is instilled into the eye and eye examined (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conjunctivitis","Blepharitis","Keratitis","Acute angle-closure glaucoma","Iritis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image of his right eye shows intense conjunctival injection (i.e. redness) with oedema with copious tearing. The corneal lesion shows central white infiltrate surrounded by a brownish ring then a ring of further white infiltrate. The brown ring is typical of a rust ring from a ferrous foreign body. Slit lamp examination would determine if the rust needs removal or not. The lesion needs treatment with topical antibiotic and steroid drops\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to answering this question is identifying that there is uptake of fluorescein to the right of the pupil (pictured), suggesting damage to the cornea. \u003Cstrong\u003EKeratitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the only corneal pathology listed, so it must be the correct option. Additionally, keratitis matches the history of gradual onset, unilateral eye pain with reduced visual acuity but preserved pupillary light reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the conjunctiva. It is more likely to be bilateral than unilateral and is not associated with reduced visual acuity. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlepharitis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the eyelid margin. Although bilateral, it is similarly not associated with reduced visual acuity. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pain associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute angle-closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by a sudden increase in intraocular pressure (IOP). As such, it classically presents with sudden onset severe pain, rather than gradual as in this case. It will also be associated with a non-reactive pupil. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIritis\u003C/strong\u003E, or anterior uveitis, is inflammation of the anterior part of the uveal tract, primarily involving the iris and sometimes the ciliary body. Pupil abnormalities may occur due to inflammation of the iris sphincter muscle, ciliary muscle spasm, or the formation of posterior synechiae (adhesions between the iris and lens). These changes can cause the pupil to become irregular, constricted, or sluggish in its response to light.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fluorescein uptake on ophthalmic examination of a red eye suggests corneal pathology."],"references":["Gilani C, Yang A, Yonkers M, Boysen-Osborn M. Differentiating urgent and emergent causes of acute red eye for the emergency physician. West J Emerg Med. 2017;18(3):509\u201317. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5488829/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85192"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"518"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17823"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17823"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/db440048-95d9-4a6e-98ea-96841b6ff5ea.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/db440048-95d9-4a6e-98ea-96841b6ff5ea.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":567,"height":379}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85192"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-14T15:26:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-14T15:28:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"518"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"quest